<section xml:id="lesson2_3" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Exploring the <c>CNOT</c> Gate</title>
  <p>
    Now we are going to use the same method to explore how the <c>CNOT</c> gate works.
    You will try all four input combinations (<m>\ket{00}</m>, <m>\ket{01}</m>,
    <m>\ket{10}</m>, and <m>\ket{11}</m>) to determine the relationship between
    inputs and outputs for the <c>CNOT</c> gate.
  </p>
  <section xml:id="lesson2_3_1">
    <title>Creating a <c>CNOT</c> gate</title>
    <sidebyside widths="75% 25%" valign="top">

      <p>
        To create a <c>CNOT</c> gate, you will need to:
      <ol>
        <li>Drag a spot (⚫) onto the top qubit,</li>
        <li>Drag a <em>NOT</em> gate tile onto the bottom qubit, aligning it vertically with the spot,</li>
        <li>Click the number at the top of the column to select them as a group, and</li>
        <li>Click the "C/S" button to connect the tiles.</li>
      </ol>
      When you are finished, you should see a line connecting the two tiles,
      indicating that you have created a <c>CNOT</c> gate.
      </p>
      <image source="CNOT.png" width="40%" />
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
      Use the circuit builder below to make a <c>CNOT</c> gate.
    </p>

    <interactive aspect="9:9" platform="javascript"
      source="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/dmfranklin/quantum-module/source/loader.js">
      <script>
        identicalCircuitWidget({
          circuit: "L2_3_2",
          instantFeedback: true,
          allowedGates: "X*"
        });
      </script>
    </interactive>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="lesson2_3_2">
    <title>Exploring the <c>CNOT</c> Gate</title>
    <p>
      Now let's explore how the <c>CNOT</c> gate works using the same method that you used to explore
      the <c>SWAP</c> gate. Try all four input combinations (<m>\ket{00}</m>, <m>\ket{01}</m>,
      <m>\ket{10}</m>, and <m>\ket{11}</m>) to determine the relationship between inputs
      and outputs for the <c>CNOT</c> gate.
    </p>
    <p>
      Place the spot (⚫) on the top qubit and the <c>NOT</c> on the bottom qubit.
    </p>

    <interactive aspect="9:9" platform="javascript"
      source="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/dmfranklin/quantum-module/source/loader.js">
      <script>
        visualizeProbabilitiesWidget({
          circuit: "Blank 2x6",
          allowedGates: "X*"
        });
      </script>
    </interactive>

    <exercise label="CNOT_truth_table">
      <title>
        <c>CNOT</c> Truth Table
      </title>
      <idx>CNOT_truth_table</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Select the picture that depicts the correct truth table for the <c>CNOT</c> gate.
          It should show the proper relationship between the four possible input and output
          combinations.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <image source="CNOTgate.png" width="100%" />
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Yes! The target qubit, the bottom qubit, toggles if and only if the control, the top qubit, is <m>
                \ket{1}</m>.</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <image source="CNOTgateWrong1.png" width="100%" />
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Make sure you hooked up your circuit correctly!</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <image source="CNOTgateWrong2.png" width="100%" />
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Make sure you hooked up your circuit correctly!</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <image source="CNOTgateWrong3.png" width="100%" />
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Make sure you hooked up your circuit correctly!</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
      <hint>
        <p>Use the circuit builder above to make the circuit.
          The bar graph below the circuit can help you to determine the outputs for different inputs.</p>
        <p>Try it with <m>\ket{10}</m> and <m>\ket{11}</m>.
          To do this, you need to use a <c>NOT</c> gates to change the input value <m>\ket{0}</m> to <m>\ket{1}</m>.
          Then, record the answers.</p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      Now that you have the full truth table for <c>CNOT</c>, you may want to write it on a page of
      notes or take a screenshot for future reference. In the following questions, you will be
      asked to calculate the results of circuits involving <c>NOT</c>, <c>SWAP</c>, and/or <c>CNOT</c> gates.
    </p>
    <exercise label="CNOT_Q1">
      <title>
        <c>CNOT</c> Question #1
      </title>
      <idx>cnot Q1</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>What is the output of the following circuit?</p>
        <image source="CNOT_Q1.png" width="66%" />
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="no">
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\ket{00}</m> or <m>\ket{⚪⚪}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Make sure you hooked up your circuit correctly!</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\ket{01}</m> or <m>\ket{⚪⚫}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Correct!</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\ket{10}</m> or <m>\ket{⚫⚪}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Make sure you hooked up your circuit correctly!</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\ket{11}</m> or <m>\ket{⚫⚫}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Make sure you hooked up your circuit correctly!</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
      <hint>
        <p>Write down the circuit and write the state of each qubit after each gate.</p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>

